<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-141-017 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 045 403</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Expert  June 1991 v6 n3 p67(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Process monitoring and diagnosis: a model-based approach.andO;(Knowledge-based diagnosis in process engineering)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dvorak, Daniel; Kuipers, Benjamin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Operator advisory systems are an important area in expert systemssince human process operators overlook relevant information, donot respond fast enough, and panic when there is a large amount ofinformation.andP;  Mimic is a model-based approach that uses apredictive model to mimic the system and when a change happens,change the model so it continues to provide a definition ofexpected behavior.andP;  Mimic tells the operators what is happeningand what to do about the situation.andP;  Benefits of Mimic includeearly detection of deviations, predicting values of unobservedvariables, predicting undesirable or hazardous conditions, andtelling what will happen when a certain control method is used.andO;The three main technologies used in Mimic are semi-quantitativesimulation: tracking, also called measurement interpretation; andmodel-based diagnosis.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Process ControlExpert SystemsArtificial IntelligenceKnowledge-Based SystemsProcess ManagementDiagnosticsOperation of Computer SystemsModelsSimulationEngineering.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartgraph.andO;Caption:   The three tasks of process monitoring. (chart)The architecture of Mimic. (chart)Tracking through a behavior graph. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>